context: At the <a0_0>end of the 16th century<a0_0/>, the Aussa Sultanate was established in the <a1_0><b9_0>Denkel lowlands of Eritrea<b9_0/><a1_0/>. The polity had come into existence in <b5_0>1577<b5_0/>, when Muhammed Jasa moved his capital from Harar to Aussa (Asaita) with the split of the Adal Sultanate into Aussa and the Sultanate of Harar. At some point after <b7_0><b8_0>1672<b8_0/><b7_0/>, Aussa declined in conjunction with Imam Umar Din bin Adam's recorded ascension to the throne. In <b6_0>1734<b6_0/>, the Afar leader <a2_0>Kedafu, head of the Mudaito clan<a2_0/>, seized power and established the <a3_0><a4_0>Mudaito Dynasty<a4_0/><a3_0/>. This marked the start of a new and more sophisticated polity that would last into the colonial period.
